data.content:
These are two distinct issues introduced by C# 15 changes:

---

**Issue 1 — `left && right` with `dynamic`**

C# 15 changed how `&&`/`||` interact with `dynamic`. The compiler now **partially resolves `&&` at compile time**: it statically resolves `operator true`/`operator false` on the non-dynamic operand for the short-circuit check, then dynamically binds `operator &`.

`IFilter` defines `operator true`/`operator false` but **not** `operator &`. The `&&` operator requires all three on the same type. Previously, the entire expression was deferred to runtime; now the compiler catches this mismatch at compile time.

**Fixes** (pick one):
```csharp
// Option A: Add operator & to the interface
interface IFilter
{
    static IFilter operator &(IFilter x, IFilter y) => x;
    static bool operator true(IFilter x) => true;
    static bool operator false(IFilter x) => false;
}

// Option B: Make both operands dynamic to fully defer binding
var combined = (dynamic)left && right;
```

---

**Issue 2 — `ref readonly` return lambda → CS0518**

CS0518 ("Predefined type is not defined or imported") means the compiler needs a well-known BCL type to emit metadata for this construct and can't find it. C# 15 requires a **new compiler-internal attribute** to represent `ref readonly` returns on synthesized delegate types for lambdas — similar to how `ref readonly` parameters needed `RequiresLocationAttribute` in C# 12.

This typically happens when the **language version and target framework are mismatched** — e.g., the SDK provides C# 15 but the project still targets `net10.0` or `net9.0`.

**Fix:**
```xml
<!-- Ensure your .csproj targets .NET 11 -->
<TargetFramework>net11.0</TargetFramework>
```

If you must target an older TFM, you can define the missing polyfill type manually (check the full CS0518 message for the exact type name) or use a named method instead of a lambda:

```csharp
class RefHelper
{
    private static int value = 42;

    // Named method instead of lambda — works on older TFMs
    public static ref readonly int GetValue() => ref value;
}
```
